[{"id":29858,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>An asymmetric carbon atom is a carbon atom that is attached to four different types of atoms or groups of atoms.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/90aaba62-174a-4ad9-a0d7-8265b5f14ec2-image.png\" style=\"width: 298px; height: 110px;\" /></p><p>Number of compounds containing asymmetric carbons are three.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29963,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Anions are more nucleophilic than neutral. So,&nbsp;<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> is least nucleophilic.<br />nucleophilicity<math><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math> density<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2b4eea1a-3e78-44ad-b5f3-c35b8df41f6b-image.png\" style=\"width: 498px; height: 217px;\" /><br /><br />Greater the delocalization of charge, lesser will be nucleophilicity.<br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29877,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Volume of N<sub>2</sub> gas is equal to 22.4 ml at STP<br />Mole of N<sub>2</sub> gas =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></math><br />Weight of N<sub>2</sub> gas =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn></math></p><p>% of N in organic compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>Hence,&nbsp;The percentage of nitrogen in the compound is 14%</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30031,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3>\\mathrm{HCHO}$","$\\mathrm{HCHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{HCHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{HCHO}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Presence of alkyl group in carbonyl compounds decreases their reactivity towards nucleophilic addition. Further greater the number of such groups lesser will be the reactivity towards nucleophilic addition $\\therefore$ correct order is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e3-car6NAUWm878ywL2eU_Y-eP_Wo5mdVl4xiEtxKzw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30037,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["3-methyl-2-pentene","4-methyl-1-pentene","3-methyl-1-pentene","2-methyl-2-pentene"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_gnU_M1Z1IcR3t2tfc92gOQJgf6Bkz8b_xwK-Us-qEA.original.fullsize.png\"><br> only 3-methyl-1-pentene has a chiral carbon","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":29741,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\text { (D) }  < (\\text { C }) < (\\text { A }) < (\\text { B })\\)","\\(\\text { (B) }  < \\text { (A) } < \\text { (C) } < \\text { (D) }\\)","\\(\\text { (A) }  < \\text { (B) } < \\text { (C) } < \\text { (D) }\\)","\\(\\text { (B) }  < \\text { (A) } < \\text { (D) } < \\text { (C) }\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"Compounds having same number of carbon atoms follow the boiling point order as:\n$(\\text { Boiling point })_{\\text {Hydrogen bonding }}>(\\text { Boiling point })_{\\text {high polanity }}>$ $(\\text { Boiling point })_{\\text {low polarity }}>(\\text { Boiling point })_{\\text {non polar }}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29874,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/58ce1ef2-0882-4d78-a20d-4f3a21002a3a-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 193px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/694138fb-3c53-4a2e-bf01-c0c8c3fb1f18-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96e5e5a7-0441-402b-9633-00a734d1304d-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 180px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/32f7b045-c748-4048-939e-344905e6431d-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A staggered conformation is a chemical conformation of an ethane-like molecule in which the substituents are at the maximum distance from each other. This requires the torsional angle to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/694138fb-3c53-4a2e-bf01-c0c8c3fb1f18-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" /></p><p>In anti conformation the dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>180</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></math> (maximum)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29764,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III","A-IV, B-III, C-II. D-I","A-I. B-II, C-IV, D-III","A-II, B-III. C-I, D-IV"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A mixture of chloroform and aniline can be separated by distillation. The boiling point of chloroform is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>°</mo></math>C, and that of aniline is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>189</mn><mo>°</mo></math>C. Therefore, distillation can be used to separate a mixture of chloroform and aniline.</p><p><b>Fractional distillation</b> is the process by which oil refineries separate crude oil into different, more useful hydrocarbon products based on their relative molecular weights in a distillation tower.</p><p>Steam Distillation is a separation process for temperature-sensitive substances. It is a particular type of distillation. Another way around is a method for separating miscible liquid bases depending upon their volatilities. Aniline - Water mixture can be separated by this technique.</p><p>For separating glycerol from spent-lye is distillation under reduced pressure because glycerol has a high boiling point and since in this method the external pressure is lowered, it boils at a lower temperature.</p><p>Hence option B is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29719,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{HCOOH}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{HCOOH}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{HCOOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{HCOOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH} > \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}\\)"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$, $\\mathrm{HCOOH}$\nThe correct order is :\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{HCOOH}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}> \\\\ & \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29840,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Let the mass of organic compound = m g</p><p>Volume of nitrogen collected = V<sub>1 </sub>mL</p><p>Room temperature = T<sub>1</sub>K</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn><mi>ml</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>280</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi>total</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub></math>= Atmospheric pressure &ndash; Aqueous tension</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>22400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gas</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi>z</mi></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>760</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>082</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>280</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00097</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>Nitrogen</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></math>g</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>728</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29937,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Acidity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math> stability of conjugate base</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d550caea-0699-4020-aaa6-9e07de2b97e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 624px; height: 87px;\" /></p><p>(Stability of conjugate bases)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29796,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Water present in the pores of the paper forms the stationary phase.","Paper sheet forms the stationary phase.","Water present in the mobile phase gets absorbed by the paper which then forms the stationary phase.","Paper and water present in its pores together form the stationary phase."],"answer":0,"solution":"The principle of paper chromatography is partition. In paper chromatography there are two phases one is the stationary phase and the other is the mobile phase. Here, water trapped in the paper acts as the stationary phase and solvent acts as the mobile phase.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29777,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/99ff2d5f-4838-45e4-b851-9e127e975b83.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 212px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8402aacc-ebaa-4bf4-a2ea-c0aa0c588375.png\" style=\"width: 196px; height: 180px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2cddf16c-778e-4631-8b28-5cbbb9999ed4.png\" style=\"width: 171px; height: 179px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93bf4470-319a-4041-bb38-365974c0b755.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 209px;\"/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Geometrical Isomerism arises due to different arrangement atoms/groups around a system where free rotation of bonds is restricted.</p><p>Generally in a geometric isomer, the atoms are bonded by a double bond that does not freely rotate, but it can also happens because of the ring structure.</p><p>The other condition to exhibit geometrical isomerism is, two atoms or groups attached to the molecule with the doubly bonded carbon atom must be different. However, it doesn't matter whether the left side groups are the same or different on the right side.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eee80f7f-c92f-436a-8677-1224c3bea8af.png\" style=\"width: 220px; height: 186px;\"/></p><p>This compound shows geometrical isomerism.</p><p>Hence option B is the answer,</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29675,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(B) & (D) only","(A) & (B) only","(B) & (C) only","(A) & (C) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oqRU_SW7CWqoGIrbCqsDBPyv5iDFJp0akuMtO71P59c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cwJidgpjf73aRvhtfm_hxTgJ-4pHYg3QNGgsWsufJqE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29703,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$q\\gt r\\gt p$","$r\\gt q\\gt p$","$q\\gt p\\gt r$","$\\mathrm{p}\\gt\\mathrm{q}\\gt\\mathrm{r}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"q is aromatic\nr is non-aromatic\np is antiaromatic\n$\\mathrm{q}>\\mathrm{r}>\\mathrm{p}$ (order of stability)\nAromatic > non-aromatic > antiaromatic","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29987,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math><mo>(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>R</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Q</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>S</mtext><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br />1. Coloured impurity <math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math> Charcoal treatment<br /><br />2. mixture of o &ndash; nitrophenol and p &ndash;nitrophenol<math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math>Steam distillation(Both form intermolecular H-Bond)<br /><br />3. Crude Naphtha<math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math>Fractional distillation<br /><br />4. mixture of glycerol and sugars <math> <mo>&#8594;</mo> </math> Distillation under reduced pressure","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29716,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\((\\mathrm{B})  < (\\mathrm{D}) < (\\mathrm{C}) < (\\mathrm{A}) < (\\mathrm{E})\\)","\\(\\text { (D) }  < \\text { (E) } < \\text { (C) } < \\text { (B) } < \\text { (A) }\\)","\\(\\text { (E) }  < \\text { (D) } < (\\text { C }) < (\\text { B }) < (\\text { A })\\)","\\(\\text { (E) }  < \\text { (D) } < \\text { (B) } < \\text { (A) } < \\text { (C) }\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"Acidic strength order :-\n$\\mathrm{B}>\\mathrm{D}>\\mathrm{C}>\\mathrm{A}>\\mathrm{E}$\nCorrect $\\mathrm{pKa}$ Order :\n$\\text { B } < \\text { D } < \\text { C } < \\text { A } < \\text { E }$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30071,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3-\\mathrm{C}- < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2-\\mathrm{CH}- < \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2- < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2- < \\mathrm{CH}- < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3-\\mathrm{C}-$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2-\\mathrm{CH}- < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3-\\mathrm{C}- < \\mathrm{CH}_3,-\\mathrm{CH}_2$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3-\\mathrm{C}- < \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2-\\mathrm{CH}-$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3$ group has $+\\mathrm{I}$ effect, as number of $-\\mathrm{CH}_3$ group increases, the inductive effect increases.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29639,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$x>y>z$","$y>z>x$","$z>x>y$","$x>z>y$"],"answer":2,"solution":"In acetone $(y)$, the carbon-oxygen bond is a localized double bond with a bond order of approximately $2$.<br><br>In the acetate ion $(z)$, there are two equivalent resonance structures that delocalize the negative charge equally over both oxygen atoms. This results in a carbon-oxygen bond order of exactly $1.5$.<br><br>In tropone $(x)$, the carbon-oxygen double bond is conjugated with the $\\pi$ system of the seven-membered ring. Polarization of the $C=O$ bond leads to a resonance structure with a single $C-O^{-}$ bond and a positive charge on the ring, forming an aromatic tropylium cation. This aromatic stabilization gives the $C=O$ bond significant single-bond character. However, because this resonance structure involves charge separation, its contribution is less than that of the neutral structure. Thus, the bond order in tropone is between $1.5$ and $2$.<br><br>Since bond length is inversely proportional to bond order, the carbon-oxygen bond length is longest for the acetate ion (bond order $1.5$), followed by tropone (bond order between $1.5$ and $2$), and shortest for acetone (bond order $2$).<br><br>Therefore, the correct order of carbon-oxygen bond length is $z > x > y$.<br><br>Answer: $z>x>y$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29980,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;Values are a measure of basicity. Higher the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;value, greater will be basicity.<br /><br />(I) Basic character &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mtext>&#8201;s-&#8201;character</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> has more % s-character than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> so it is less basic as compare to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> Hence <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>.</mo></math><br /><br />(II) In the (ii) structure lone pair present on the N atom is involved in aromaticity so, it is difficult to donate. Hence, least basic<br /><br />Thus, the correct order will be: <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30001,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" height=\"110\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image23-e5c59b8f-9d70-494a-a7c6-332dd2d4e600.jpg\" width=\"251\" />","<img alt=\"\" height=\"116\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image24-8cc29c79-b8a9-4030-aa32-b4bac9aa23f9.jpg\" width=\"265\" />","<img alt=\"\" height=\"128\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image25-b1e875c2-630c-4fee-94f7-4d5e0681f406.jpg\" width=\"253\" />","<img alt=\"\" height=\"90\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image26-aff0d20a-5e77-48f0-88bc-7276c551c3fb.jpg\" width=\"287\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"Positional isomers are constitutional isomers that have the same carbon skeleton and the same functional groups but differ from each other in the location of the functional groups in the carbon chain.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Partition chromatography is based on continuous differential partitioning of components of a mixture between stationary and mobile phases. Paper chromatography is a type of partition chromatography. In paper chromatography, a special quality paper known as chromatography paper is used. Chromatography paper contains water trapped in it, which acts as the stationary phase.</p><p>The relative partition&nbsp;of each component of the mixture is expressed in terms of its retardation factor i.e. R<sub>f</sub> value</p><p>R<sub>f</sub> =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travel</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>from</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>base</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>line</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travel</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solvent</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>from</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>base</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>line</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29742,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\(d > a > c > b\\)","a \\( > \\) b \\( > \\) c \\( > \\) d","\\(d > c > b > a\\)","\\(c > b > d > \\) a"],"answer":2,"solution":"As we know compound (d) is aromatic and the compound (a) is anti-aromatic. Hence compound (d) is most stable and compound (a) is least stable among these in compound (b) and (c) carbon atom of that positive charge is $\\mathrm{sp}^3$ hybridised they on the basis of angle strain theory compound (c) is more stable than compound (b).\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b3DV3CpFQU7gTtCp99ww3hFbDoUJUp5-Y_l2lbxNps.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29994,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/123456aaaaaaa.PNG\" style=\"width: 52px; height: 61px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/234567.PNG\" style=\"width: 60px; height: 59px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/345678acsfadfad.PNG\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 68px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/456789.PNG\" style=\"width: 64px; height: 59px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"In A,B,D entire ring involved in delocalisation and follow&nbsp;huckel rule of (4n+2)pi electrons. so, they are aromatic and are more stable.<br />While in C one carbon is&nbsp;sp<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;so&nbsp;non planar. so, non aromatic and it is&nbsp;less stable.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29760,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["crystallisation","distillation under reduced pressure","distillation","steam distillation"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Steam distillation technique is applied to separate substances which are steam volatile and are immiscible with water.</p><p>As the organic compounds steam volatile and are miscible with water vapour in the vapour phase, steam distillation will be the most suitable method for extraction of oils from flowers. Steam distillation is carried out by passing dry steam through the plant material whereby the steam volatile compounds are volatilised, condensed and collected in receivers. The most common use of steam distillation is the extraction of natural products from plant materials. It has been in use for essential oil extraction for many years.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30060,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["3, 3- dimethyl -1- hydroxy cyclohexane","1,1-dimethyl -3- cyclohexanol","3,3- dimethyl -1- cyclohexanol","1,1 - dimethyl -3- hydroxy cyclohexane"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29737,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A)-(II), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(III)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(I), (B)-(III), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yYu-RzwLfentMRasMMSGWloVP-zXlXtQWdZbulG84ow.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Position isomers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9PI_c_15H_Q2qmVFXbaOzf6kSxrkyJKaDtIwthtE2eI.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Metamers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EhLSR1ceWgwv1Br8isbI4XaINmPCr1wKTspSuWMKeSA.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Functional isomers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5U5Rk697gnGmkwORJFdJvFXhiLRe4b-e24YwrEK8J7g.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Chain isomers","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29848,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Steam distillation","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ft</mi></math> long column of silica gel","Sublimation","Preparative TLC (Thin Layer Chromatography)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/acb15856-5763-459b-84d4-d44d68f02551-image.png\" style=\"width: 317px; height: 300px;\" /></p><p>Solvent polarity has been related to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math> value of nitrocompounds.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mi>mg</mi></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>-nitrophenol and picric acid have different <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math> value on silica gel plate</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;Preparative TLC is best to separate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mi>mg</mi></math> of para nitrophenol and picric acid</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29969,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding and resonance stabilization, enol content is maximum in&nbsp;<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/486fd3a3-7536-4a03-a497-4cb7b0810240-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 178px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29860,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> (Solid)","U.V. Light","Visualisation agent as a component of mobile phase","Spraying of an appropriate reagent"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Thin Layer Chromatography is a technique used to isolate non-volatile mixtures. The experiment is conducted on a sheet of aluminium foil, plastic, or glass which is coated with a thin layer of adsorbent material. The material usually used is aluminium oxide, cellulose, or silica gel.</p><p>The sample spots can be observed under a UV light chamber,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;solid or by spraying of an appropriate reagent which can react with the sample spot.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]